Day 1 — What is JFrog? Platform Overview
What is JFrog?
JFrog is a DevOps platform centered around artifact management — storing, organizing, securing, and distributing the software artifacts (binaries, packages, Docker images, etc.) that your CI/CD pipeline produces and consumes.

Think of JFrog as the single source of truth for all your binaries — every build artifact, every dependency, every Docker image passes through it.

The Problem JFrog Solves
Without a central artifact manager:

Teams download dependencies directly from the internet (slow, unreliable, uncontrolled)
No traceability — which binary was deployed to production?
No security — no scanning of what's pulled in
No governance — anyone can publish anything anywhere
Build tools reach external registries directly — firewall and network issues

JFrog Product Suite
Product	Purpose
Artifactory	Universal artifact repository manager — the core product
Xray	Security & compliance scanning of artifacts
Pipelines	CI/CD pipeline orchestration
Distribution	Distribute release bundles to edge nodes globally
Connect	IoT device management and distribution
Catalog	Open-source package metadata and risk management
The most important for daily use: Artifactory + Xray.

What is Artifactory?
Artifactory is a universal binary repository manager that supports virtually every package format:

Package Type	Format
Java	Maven, Gradle, Ivy, SBT
JavaScript	npm, YarnKey Concepts
Repository — A storage location for a specific type of artifact
Artifact — Any binary: a JAR, a Docker image, an npm package, a .zip file
Build Info — Metadata linking a build to all its inputs and outputs
Package Type — The format/technology of the repository (Maven, Docker, npm, etc.)
Python	PyPI
Containers	Docker, OCI
Infrastructure	Helm (Kubernetes charts)
OS packages	Debian, RPM, Alpine
Generic binaries	Any file type
And more	Go, NuGet, CocoaPods, Composer...
